> Hmm, why are you wrong? It seems the error is correctly gone for the first function call.

It seems there are cases where Psalm isn't going into if blocks even if one can be 100% sure they would be executed. The following gives an error, but shouldn't:

```php
<?php // --taint-analysis

/**
 * @psalm-pure
 */
function foo(string $string)
{
    if (true) {
        return 'asdf';
    }

    return $string;
}

echo foo($_GET['bar']);
```

I am actually not sure how the taint analysis behaves with conditional checks. (i.e. whether it supports it at all or not)

